1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,320
 Good morning after everybody and you know I love being back here.

2
00:00:06,320 --> 00:00:10,320
 This is my favorite pulpit in the whole world.

3
00:00:10,320 --> 00:00:16,880
 Well not the pulpit but today I want to share something special.

4
00:00:16,880 --> 00:00:20,480
 Something very dear to my heart.

5
00:00:20,480 --> 00:00:24,080
 At the Vine this year God has given us a vision

6
00:00:24,080 --> 00:00:28,960
 for uncharted territories and Pastor Andrew asked me to

7
00:00:28,960 --> 00:00:34,240
 bring a word of encouragement in that area.

8
00:00:34,240 --> 00:00:40,560
 One of my personal uncharted territories that I have discovered this year

9
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:45,680
 is would you believe pickleball.

10
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:49,040
 Yeah.

11
00:00:49,040 --> 00:00:57,680
 I have been well and truly hooked. You might say

12
00:00:57,680 --> 00:01:05,680
 pickled on it. The rules are simple. The game is easy for beginners to

13
00:01:05,680 --> 00:01:10,880
 learn but as I found it can develop into a fast-paced

14
00:01:10,880 --> 00:01:17,440
 competitive game. I like that. Now the byproduct for me has been a

15
00:01:17,440 --> 00:01:23,360
 whole new group of friends and fellow players.

16
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:30,000
 A community with a common denominator.

17
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:34,640
 That got me thinking about the importance of the workplace.

18
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:40,720
 Another community with an albeit slightly different common

19
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:43,680
 denominator.

20
00:01:43,680 --> 00:01:47,200
 It's great we've just been able to pray for Hong Kong. Hong Kong is

21
00:01:47,200 --> 00:01:52,960
 known for its highly fast-paced and competitive work environment particularly

22
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:56,720
 as a leading international financial hub.

23
00:01:56,720 --> 00:02:01,200
 The idea for this talk actually came from an alpha meeting.

24
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:04,400
 Anyone likes alpha? Good. I was at recently

25
00:02:04,400 --> 00:02:11,520
 and it was reported that globally only two percent of alpha courses

26
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:16,320
 are in the workplace whereas in Hong Kong that figure is

27
00:02:16,320 --> 00:02:23,360
 actually 14 percent. Seven times. And that alpha courses have been

28
00:02:23,360 --> 00:02:27,440
 conducted here in more than 50 industries and you'll

29
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:31,840
 see a picture of them on the screen.

30
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:39,520
 It got me thinking. If we as a church are serious

31
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:47,040
 about uncharted territories, surely, surely, surely

32
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:54,640
 one of our major priorities must be the reason this city is what it is.

33
00:02:54,640 --> 00:03:04,080
 Its workplace and the approximately 3.8 million people in it.

34
00:03:04,720 --> 00:03:12,960
 Do you know when people are not sleeping most of their time is spent working?

35
00:03:12,960 --> 00:03:19,920
 The average Christian spends less than two percent of their waking time

36
00:03:19,920 --> 00:03:26,960
 at church. And work was actually God's idea.

37
00:03:26,960 --> 00:03:31,440
 Right at the beginning of scripture after God created the heavens and the

38
00:03:31,440 --> 00:03:36,000
 earth and then man we read in Genesis 2.15.

39
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:44,240
 The Lord God took the man and put him in the garden of Eden to work it

40
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:48,000
 and to take care of it.

41
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:53,200
 What I'm going to share today is part of my

42
00:03:53,200 --> 00:03:59,520
 personal journey. This picture I put up here.

43
00:03:59,520 --> 00:04:06,560
 It tells a million stories.

44
00:04:06,560 --> 00:04:12,000
 Almost everybody calls me Pastor John.

45
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:18,400
 I prefer saying I am John who happens to be a pastor.

46
00:04:18,400 --> 00:04:26,560
 I came to Hong Kong in 1987 as a businessman. I loved my job.

47
00:04:26,560 --> 00:04:30,480
 I was a general manager for the Hong Kong operation of AXA,

48
00:04:30,480 --> 00:04:34,000
 one of the largest insurance companies in the world.

49
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:41,760
 I was a businessman for longer than I've been a pastor.

50
00:04:41,760 --> 00:04:48,640
 33 years, three months, and three days.

51
00:04:48,640 --> 00:04:55,520
 I mean not exactly but you know what three in Cantonese is, right? Good.

52
00:04:56,480 --> 00:05:03,360
 And I'm often asked a question. How long, how long have you been in

53
00:05:03,360 --> 00:05:11,280
 full-time ministry? My answer, I have always been in full-time

54
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:14,240
 ministry. Can I hear I meant to that? Are you there

55
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:20,080
 this morning? Good. The truth is the reality

56
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:24,640
 is I reached more people for Christ in the insurance industry

57
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:30,640
 than I do as a pastor. I spend far too much of my time now as a

58
00:05:30,640 --> 00:05:34,640
 pastor with Christians like you.

59
00:05:34,640 --> 00:05:42,800
 And I want to start off by destroying the myth

60
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:47,280
 that had me one day working for the dollar sign

61
00:05:47,280 --> 00:05:52,880
 and the next day having a permanent halo on my head. Yeah right.

62
00:05:52,880 --> 00:05:58,480
 Church history has consistently been ready to

63
00:05:58,480 --> 00:06:03,440
 to conveniently put things into two boxes.

64
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:10,640
 Over here we have sacred and over here we have secular.

65
00:06:10,640 --> 00:06:17,360
 This has not been my experience. In the early 80s I was a reasonably

66
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:21,440
 successful sales manager of a UK insurance company, a

67
00:06:21,440 --> 00:06:28,240
 subsidiary of a merchant bank. When in my late 20s I realised

68
00:06:28,240 --> 00:06:34,160
 I had everything, practically everything the world could throw at me

69
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:41,840
 in a material sense. But yet I had a gaping chasm in my heart.

70
00:06:41,840 --> 00:06:48,640
 A Christ-shaped hole to be precise. I first saw this in other people who

71
00:06:48,640 --> 00:06:55,840
 clearly had found something I didn't have and something I was looking for.

72
00:06:55,840 --> 00:07:03,680
 And so I recommitted my life. The workplace became my mission field

73
00:07:03,680 --> 00:07:09,520
 from day one as everyone was curious what had happened to me.

74
00:07:09,520 --> 00:07:13,040
 Although I was the company's leading sales manager

75
00:07:13,040 --> 00:07:20,160
 my lifestyle had been decidedly self-absorbed. To be honest

76
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:28,320
 foul-mouthed, driven, workaholic. But now

77
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:33,280
 I had a new boss and was willing to follow him

78
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:38,480
 to the ends of the earth. Literally.

79
00:07:40,800 --> 00:07:45,920
 In 1987, I've got another picture for you, I was asked to consider to take my family

80
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:53,600
 my wife Sandra, my two sons Paul and Matt and even my old English sheepdog Bella

81
00:07:53,600 --> 00:07:59,520
 to Hong Kong for three years. Don't believe that when anyone tells you that.

82
00:07:59,520 --> 00:08:03,360
 For three years to start an investment services

83
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:07,520
 company for National Mutu, our new parent company.

84
00:08:07,520 --> 00:08:12,000
 Our only previous visit to Hong Kong was 1981.

85
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:19,200
 Sandra took one look down Nathan Road and declared, "You won't get me living here

86
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:24,400
 in a million years." Moral, never say never.

87
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:30,400
 It wasn't that funny.

88
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:39,440
 Maybe it was. My arrival was coincident with the

89
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:46,880
 famous stock market crash of 1987. Black Monday. And I ended up

90
00:08:46,880 --> 00:08:52,880
 with the toughest period of my business life and it was humbling.

91
00:08:52,880 --> 00:08:56,960
 I wish I could tell the whole story but suffice to say that

92
00:08:56,960 --> 00:09:01,680
 in that time God gave me a deep love for Hong Kong

93
00:09:01,680 --> 00:09:06,800
 and a vision for his church and in particular for evangelism.

94
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:11,600
 And 38 years later I'm still here.

95
00:09:11,600 --> 00:09:22,000
 And I can give testimony to 38 years of God's grace.

96
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:30,800
 My thinking on the topic of faith and the workplace

97
00:09:30,800 --> 00:09:34,560
 has been heavily shaped by Ed Silvozo's book,

98
00:09:34,560 --> 00:09:40,000
 "Anointed for Business." It's here I let you into a little secret.

99
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:47,120
 I'd always secretly harbored a desire to be a pastor.

100
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:52,320
 But this book and the group of insurance staff that I gathered around me to study

101
00:09:52,320 --> 00:09:56,240
 it, we were called FISH, Fellowship of Insurance Staff in Hong

102
00:09:56,240 --> 00:10:04,800
 Kong. It's good, eh? It told me this. It told me I already was a pastor.

103
00:10:04,800 --> 00:10:14,720
 All work was worship and every Christian is a minister. I was a marketplace pastor.

104
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:18,080
 I learned through this book and through this time that

105
00:10:18,080 --> 00:10:25,760
 every business is God's business. The notion that labour for profit

106
00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:29,920
 and worship of God are now and have always been worlds apart

107
00:10:29,920 --> 00:10:38,880
 is absolutely false. There is no sacred and secular divide.

108
00:10:38,880 --> 00:10:45,840
 I mean look at the early church founders. They were mostly community leaders and

109
00:10:45,840 --> 00:10:51,440
 highly successful business people. The writing of the gospels was trusted

110
00:10:51,440 --> 00:10:58,400
 to Luke, a medical doctor. Matthew, a retired tax collector. Mark,

111
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:02,400
 the manager of a family trust. And John, a food supplier,

112
00:11:02,400 --> 00:11:10,960
 a fishy food supplier. In the book of Acts, Lydia was a dealer in purple cloth.

113
00:11:10,960 --> 00:11:17,120
 Dorcas was a clothes designer. And yet in modern times and often in how

114
00:11:17,120 --> 00:11:22,240
 things are spoken about in today's church, the perceived wall between

115
00:11:22,240 --> 00:11:28,400
 commercial pursuit and service to God continues to be a barrier to advancing

116
00:11:28,400 --> 00:11:33,360
 the kingdom. I love this quote from Ken Costa in his

117
00:11:33,360 --> 00:11:39,440
 book, God at Work. God loves you. God loves the work

118
00:11:39,440 --> 00:11:46,160
 he has called you to. I want to push this a bit further. Perhaps some of you in the

119
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:50,880
 room are doctors. Doctors like Luke. Managers of family

120
00:11:50,880 --> 00:11:56,000
 businesses like Mark. Merchants and retail owners like Lydia.

121
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:01,600
 Or even tax collectors like Matthew. Can you put your hand up?

122
00:12:01,600 --> 00:12:04,640
 We'll pray for you afterwards.

123
00:12:04,640 --> 00:12:10,160
 Each one of us is placed in a sphere of influence.

124
00:12:10,160 --> 00:12:13,200
 And the question that we should be asking ourselves is,

125
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:19,600
 what does uncharted look like for me where I spend the majority of my time?

126
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:25,280
 Where I'm in my workplace? Where I am with my colleagues?

127
00:12:25,280 --> 00:12:29,760
 And that is what I want to turn to in this message.

128
00:12:29,760 --> 00:12:36,480
 I have three uncharted expectations for the workplace that I believe can

129
00:12:36,480 --> 00:12:40,480
 really shift how we act, think,

130
00:12:40,480 --> 00:12:46,560
 and live for the gospel in Hong Kong. And here is the first one. Number one, I

131
00:12:46,560 --> 00:12:54,320
 don't have a job. I have a calling. I want you to realize that you

132
00:12:54,320 --> 00:12:57,280
 are called.

133
00:12:57,280 --> 00:13:05,680
 A simple illustration will help me. One day in 1671, Christopher Wren, the

134
00:13:05,680 --> 00:13:08,720
 designer of St Paul's Cathedral in London,

135
00:13:08,720 --> 00:13:15,600
 observed three bricklayers on a scaffold. One was crouched, one was half

136
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:19,200
 standing, and the other was standing tall, working

137
00:13:19,200 --> 00:13:22,800
 very hard and fast. To the first bricklayer, Christopher Wren

138
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:28,000
 asked the question, "What are you doing?" To which the bricklayer replied, "I'm a

139
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:33,440
 bricklayer. I'm working hard laying bricks to feed my

140
00:13:33,440 --> 00:13:35,920
 family."

141
00:13:36,320 --> 00:13:40,880
 The second bricklayer said, "I'm a builder.

142
00:13:40,880 --> 00:13:46,640
 I'm building a wall." But the third bricklayer, the most

143
00:13:46,640 --> 00:13:49,520
 productive of the three and the future leader of the group,

144
00:13:49,520 --> 00:13:52,560
 when asked the question, "What are you doing?"

145
00:13:52,560 --> 00:13:57,440
 replied with a gleam in his eye, "I'm a cathedral builder.

146
00:13:57,440 --> 00:14:02,720
 I'm building a great cathedral to the almighty."

147
00:14:03,280 --> 00:14:09,920
 Friends, I am passionate. I'm passionate for you to see today that your work

148
00:14:09,920 --> 00:14:13,360
 is not just like the man who described himself

149
00:14:13,360 --> 00:14:17,440
 as a bricklayer. Your work is not about a monthly paycheck,

150
00:14:17,440 --> 00:14:22,320
 although that's very important in Hong Kong, it's very expensive.

151
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:25,920
 It's not even like a builder as a means to build

152
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:29,440
 a successful career for yourself, even though that

153
00:14:29,440 --> 00:14:35,840
 also is important. But I want you to see yourself as a cathedral builder,

154
00:14:35,840 --> 00:14:42,640
 a kingdom builder. The fact is over 90 percent of Hong Kong people

155
00:14:42,640 --> 00:14:47,760
 have yet to encounter the saving power of Jesus.

156
00:14:47,760 --> 00:14:52,480
 And where do we find these people? I'll tell you where.

157
00:14:52,480 --> 00:14:57,440
 In our offices, in our schools, or other places of work.

158
00:14:57,440 --> 00:15:04,560
 40, 50, 60, 70, or even more hours per week.

159
00:15:04,560 --> 00:15:11,200
 Can you see that you are not just called to lay bricks or even build walls?

160
00:15:11,200 --> 00:15:15,040
 But there is a higher calling. It's a calling that's not

161
00:15:15,040 --> 00:15:19,440
 just for pastors or church workers, but for the very people

162
00:15:19,440 --> 00:15:26,880
 who are sitting alongside most of those who are working 40, 50, 60, or 70 hours a week.

163
00:15:26,880 --> 00:15:35,680
 You. You. And you guys up there. One of my favorite all-time books is

164
00:15:35,680 --> 00:15:40,080
 "The Call," written by Os Guinness, who I've had the privilege to

165
00:15:40,080 --> 00:15:45,440
 meet on a number of occasions. He says this, "No idea short of God's call can

166
00:15:45,440 --> 00:15:52,640
 ground and fulfill the truest human desire for purpose and fulfillment."

167
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:59,360
 But the Christian world often mistakes the word "call"

168
00:15:59,360 --> 00:16:04,400
 for being called to what we call full-time ministry.

169
00:16:04,400 --> 00:16:10,240
 That's wrong. Friends, I need to tell you something.

170
00:16:10,240 --> 00:16:17,040
 You are called. You are called. Whether you're a preacher or

171
00:16:17,040 --> 00:16:22,320
 people call you a super apostle, whether you're a bank manager, a school

172
00:16:22,320 --> 00:16:26,880
 teacher, or a full-time mom, whether you minister to drug addicts or

173
00:16:26,880 --> 00:16:31,840
 street sleepers, or you wash dishes in a cha-chan-teng,

174
00:16:31,840 --> 00:16:39,840
 you are called. I think this raises an important question.

175
00:16:39,840 --> 00:16:47,280
 Does our calling change, or is our calling always constant?

176
00:16:47,280 --> 00:16:56,000
 And in a way, the answer is yes and no. Yes, in a way that we might

177
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:59,280
 shift our day-to-day work within the calling we have, like

178
00:16:59,280 --> 00:17:03,680
 me from the marketplace to the church, but no in a sense that the

179
00:17:03,680 --> 00:17:07,920
 calling is always to the bigger picture of the kingdom of God,

180
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:11,600
 regardless of what we do.

181
00:17:11,840 --> 00:17:17,680
 My job today is to encourage you to see the big picture.

182
00:17:17,680 --> 00:17:21,120
 And this is important. You might be wrestling with a

183
00:17:21,120 --> 00:17:24,960
 nagging feeling that you have the wrong calling,

184
00:17:24,960 --> 00:17:28,400
 or think God might have better callings than

185
00:17:28,400 --> 00:17:33,120
 other callings. You might say, "I get John that we all have a calling, but

186
00:17:33,120 --> 00:17:40,160
 as a lawyer, I have a lesser calling than you as a pastor." Surely,

187
00:17:40,160 --> 00:17:44,080
 and to answer this, when we look at the first

188
00:17:44,080 --> 00:17:51,440
 church in Acts chapter 2, post-Pentecost, we read

189
00:17:51,440 --> 00:17:59,440
 this, Acts 2 47, "And numbers, and the Lord

190
00:17:59,440 --> 00:18:07,760
 added to their number daily." Daily, daily

191
00:18:07,760 --> 00:18:11,120
 those who are being saved. And where do we go

192
00:18:11,120 --> 00:18:20,320
 daily? I guarantee it's not 22 Burroughs Street, Wanchai, unless your name's Andrew.

193
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:26,240
 One thing I've always been so grateful for

194
00:18:26,240 --> 00:18:29,440
 here at the Vine over many years of God's grace, is

195
00:18:29,440 --> 00:18:35,360
 always said to us that the church is not the four walls of the building.

196
00:18:35,360 --> 00:18:39,840
 Ed Silvozo again, "As long as we believe that the church was born within four

197
00:18:39,840 --> 00:18:42,720
 walls, we will always need four walls to have a

198
00:18:42,720 --> 00:18:45,040
 church."

199
00:18:45,040 --> 00:18:51,920
 Jesus lived on earth 33 years. I don't know if it's 33 years, three

200
00:18:51,920 --> 00:18:58,400
 months, and three days by the way, but it was 33 years. Only three of them,

201
00:18:58,400 --> 00:19:03,280
 only three of them are in what we call ministry.

202
00:19:03,280 --> 00:19:09,120
 He was the carpenter's son. He was born in the marketplace. It's not

203
00:19:09,120 --> 00:19:13,200
 difficult for Jesus' neighbors to see him as a businessman, as they may have

204
00:19:13,200 --> 00:19:19,120
 purchased his products. Most of Jesus' followers remained in

205
00:19:19,120 --> 00:19:23,680
 full-time business. This was possible because they saw the

206
00:19:23,680 --> 00:19:28,320
 marketplace as their parish, and their business as their pulpit.

207
00:19:28,320 --> 00:19:32,320
 To them, witnessing was not an occasional activity,

208
00:19:32,320 --> 00:19:35,280
 but a lifestyle.

209
00:19:35,280 --> 00:19:41,440
 The book of Acts unfolds the stories of believers who did more than tell people

210
00:19:41,440 --> 00:19:47,520
 about Jesus in the marketplace. They also witnessed a steady stream of signs

211
00:19:47,520 --> 00:19:52,480
 and wonders. I don't know if you know this, but in fact

212
00:19:52,480 --> 00:19:59,440
 only one of the 40 extraordinary manifestations of God's

213
00:19:59,440 --> 00:20:05,520
 power recorded in Acts happened in a religious venue.

214
00:20:05,520 --> 00:20:08,880
 The healing of the lame man at the temple gate

215
00:20:08,880 --> 00:20:14,160
 called "Beautiful." Most of the spiritual wonders were facilitated by people like

216
00:20:14,160 --> 00:20:19,120
 Paul, Priscilla, and Aquila, who as ministry and

217
00:20:19,120 --> 00:20:25,040
 business partners are classic examples of marketplace Christians.

218
00:20:25,040 --> 00:20:31,920
 Today, millions of men and women are similarly called to full-time ministry

219
00:20:31,920 --> 00:20:38,800
 in business, education, in government, the marketplace. Unfortunately,

220
00:20:38,800 --> 00:20:41,920
 many of these marketplace Christians feel like

221
00:20:41,920 --> 00:20:45,760
 second-class citizens when compared to people who serve

222
00:20:45,760 --> 00:20:49,280
 full-time in the church or in a missionary context.

223
00:20:49,280 --> 00:20:56,080
 This should not be the case. It is imperative that they realize

224
00:20:56,080 --> 00:21:00,240
 not only is it okay to do ministry in the marketplace,

225
00:21:00,240 --> 00:21:06,000
 but that God has specifically called them and anointed them for it.

226
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:10,480
 By anointed, I mean they have been chosen and empowered by the Holy Spirit

227
00:21:10,480 --> 00:21:16,640
 for a divinely sanctured assignment. By ministry, I mean they can do more than

228
00:21:16,640 --> 00:21:20,720
 just witness. They can bring transformation to their

229
00:21:20,720 --> 00:21:26,400
 jobs and then to their cities as happened in the first century.

230
00:21:26,400 --> 00:21:32,640
 Most marketplace Christians already know that their ministry and occupation

231
00:21:32,640 --> 00:21:39,360
 are somehow connected, but they do not comprehend exactly how.

232
00:21:39,360 --> 00:21:43,680
 Christian author Jean Evith says this, "The priesthood of all believers

233
00:21:43,680 --> 00:21:46,800
 did not make everybody into church workers.

234
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:52,960
 Rather, it turned every kind of work into a sacred calling." I love this.

235
00:21:52,960 --> 00:21:57,600
